[start section id="20112"]

#1 Pneumonia, presumed healthcare associated
Mrs. Duran has had significant improvement since starting antibiotics.  For now, we will plan to continue with vancomycin dosed according to her random level, cefepime 2-g after dialysis only on dialysis days, and Cipro 400-mg IV every 24-hours, given after dialysis on dialysis days.  We will provide her with an incentive spirometer and an Acapella valve.  Blood cultures were drawn at dialysis and again in the Emergency Department, results are currently pending.  We will adjust antibiotic therapy based on culture results.  We will check a sputum specimen for Gram stain, culture, and susceptibilities.  We will wean her oxygen as tolerated.
#2 Fever and chills
This could be related to pneumonia, bacteremia, her pulmonary emboli, or the splenic infarct.  As above, we have started empiric antibiotic therapy for her presumed pneumonia.  We will monitor the results of her blood cultures and tailor antibiotic therapy appropriately.
#3 Pulmonary emboli with history of DVT
At this time, following discussion with Vascular Medicine, we do not feel that her pulmonary emboli are symptomatic.  Given that the source, her AV graft, shows only a small residual thrombus, and given concerns that she may be at increased risk for bleeding with full-dose anticoagulation, we will not provide treatment at this time.  However, if she continues to be hypoxemic and/or develops hemodynamic compromise, we may need to start empiric anticoagulation.  We will monitor closely in case the pulmonary emboli are indeed the cause of her symptoms rather than a possible infectious process.
#4 Splenic infarct
Given concern that the source could be a possible valvular thrombus or aortic thrombus or plaque, we are obtaining an emergent TEE tonight.  If this does show thrombus, we will start full-dose anticoagulation.  In this case, we feel that the benefits of anticoagulation would outweigh the risks.  While there is a theoretical risk of splenic hemorrhage, we also feel the benefit of anticoagulation would outweigh a possible complication in this regard.  Hopefully, we will not have to provide anticoagulation.  In the meantime, Mrs. Duran's pain has resolved, although we will have available as-needed Tylenol and low-dose oxycodone.
#5 Chronic kidney disease, on hemodialysis every Monday, Wednesday, and Friday
I greatly appreciate the prompt evaluation of Dr. Jean Patton; I had the privilege of meeting with her in the Emergency Department this evening.  She provided recommendations which we will follow; at this time it does not appear that Mrs. Duran has evidence of volume overload requiring emergent dialysis.  We will have her on a diabetic and dialysis diet and provide her with a fluid restriction.  I will not replace her slightly low-potassium at this time but will recheck electrolytes in the morning.
#6 Diabetes mellitus
We will check glucose four times daily, provide her with a diabetic and dialysis diet, and continue her NPH insulin.  We will give her usual 4 units this evening but will give her a reduced dose of 20 units (her normal is 28 units) in the morning pending resumption of normal oral intake and depending on her glucose levels.  Her last hemoglobin A1C of May 17, 2010, was 6.7.
#7 History of diastolic heart failure
Mrs. Duran appears euvolemic, although she does have a significantly elevated NT-proBNP which is in the setting of her chronic hemodialysis.  We will closely monitor her fluid balance.
#8 Coronary artery disease based on positive dobutamine stress ECHO
Mrs. Duran did have an elevated troponin of 0.08.  This was stable, and her value was previously 0.07 times three on August 9, 2009.  I also reviewed her ECG.  At this time, I do not feel that she has had an acute coronary syndrome, but the elevated troponins are related to her chronic hemodialysis.  We will continue her aspirin, metoprolol, and Zocor.
#9 History of hypertension
We will continue Mrs. Duran's metoprolol.
#10 History of GERD
We will continue omeprazole.
#11 Gout
We will continue allopurinol.
#12 Depression
We will continue Lexapro.
#13 Macrocytic anemia
Mrs. Duran likely has anemia of chronic kidney disease, but she does have a macrocytosis which is longstanding.  I note that her B12, folate, and TSH from a year ago are unremarkable.  We will check a peripheral smear.  She will continue with outpatient treatment as indicated.
#14 Mild thrombocytopenia
This has been intermittent and chronic based on review of her previous labs.  I wonder if her quinine could be contributing.  Per my discussion with Pharmacy tonight, quinine is restricted only to patients with malaria so we will not provide this medication unless she develops significant leg cramps at the time of dialysis.
#15 Debility
Mrs. Duran typically can only stand briefly for transfers and is generally not ambulatory.  She uses a wheelchair for mobility.  We will have physical therapy work with her while she is hospitalized.
#16 Strict isolation
Mrs. Duran has history of VRE.
#17 DVT prophylaxis
We will provide Subcu heparin twice-daily for DVT prophylaxis unless Mrs. Duran is found to have evidence of valvular or aortic thrombosis, in which case we will provide full-dose anticoagulation with IV heparin.
#18 Code status
I discussed this at length with Mrs. Duran and her family members.  For now, she will be full code.  She will speak with her family members later.  She previously has been full code, although her last hospitalization she was DNR/DNI.  Her family is not sure if she fully understood what this meant.  This can be readdressed during this hospitalization.
ADDENDUM
TEE fortunately did not show evidence of any intracardiac thrombus or mass.  There was no mobile aortic atheroma or atrial shunt.  LVEF was 65%.  There was mild RV enlargement but normal RV function.
I met just after the TEE was completed at midnight with Mrs. Duran's family members and reviewed the results and our plan of care.  I greatly appreciate the expertise of Dr. Biggs in performing the TEE.

