[start section id="20102"]

Fever, nausea, shortness-of-breath.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Duran is a delightful 84-year-old female with a complex past medical history of chronic kidney disease on hemodialysis every Monday, Wednesday, Friday; diabetes mellitus type-2; diastolic heart failure; coronary artery disease; hypertension; history of prior DVT; and history of colon cancer with recurrence status-post bowel resection.  History was obtained from Mrs. Duran, her family members, Dr. Deborah Frampton, and the MFHNH medical record.
Briefly, Mrs. Duran was in her usual state of health until yesterday when she developed left upper quadrant pain.  This morning, while at dialysis, she had nausea, fevers, and chills.  Her temperature was elevated at 38.3.  Blood cultures were drawn and she was given a dose of Ancef 1.5 g.  Her blood pressure was stable; 1.3 L of fluid was drawn off.  She then returned to her assisted-living facility where she was reportedly found to be slumped over her wheelchair with oxygen saturations in the upper 80% range and systolic blood pressure in the 70s.  She was started on oxygen, and EMS was called; they found a systolic blood pressure of approximately 110 and brought Mrs. Duran to the Neola Family Dentistry Health Care Center.
In the Emergency Department, Mrs. Duran was noted initially to have decreased level of responsiveness, but when she was transferred from the gurney to the bed and repositioned, she was more alert, but she was only speaking in short sentences because of dyspnea.  Her temperature was elevated at 38.2.  She was noted to be hypoxemic, and she was started on supplemental oxygen at 4 L by nasal cannula.  Chest x-ray, which I reviewed, showed a patchy consolidation in the left lung base and a new small left pleural effusion with stable pulmonary venous hypertension.  Labs showed hemoglobin of 10.1 with an elevated MCV of 107.3.  WBC normal at 9.6.  Platelets somewhat low at 109.  Electrolytes were remarkable for a slightly low-potassium of 3.3 and a creatinine of 2.6 with a bicarb of 33.  Lactate was normal at 0.8.  Troponin was elevated at 0.08 times two; this has been noted previously.  Her NT-proBNP was significantly elevated at 32,511.  Amylase and lipase were unremarkable.  Glucose was 131.
Given concern for pneumonia, Mrs. Duran was empirically given vancomycin 2-g, cefepime 2-g, and Cipro 400-mg IV for treatment of presumed healthcare-associated pneumonia.  However, because Mrs. Duran also reported left upper quadrant pain/pleuritic pain, she underwent a chest CT angiogram and CT of the abdomen and pelvis.  Noted were pulmonary emboli within segmental pulmonary arteries of the right lower lobe and a new moderate-sized wedge-shaped splenic infarct.
I met with Mrs. Duran in the Emergency Department and had the privilege of meeting with Dr. Frampton.  I also met with Mrs. Duran's multiple family members.  Mrs. Duran was sitting up in her hospital gurney.  She was alert and awake.  She had nonlabored respirations, but she did have apparent conversational dyspnea.  She had a very rare nonproductive cough.  She was able to lie supine, which did not worsen or otherwise change her breathing.  She said her abdominal pain had resolved.  She said she was feeling much better than she had been earlier today.  I was able to wean down her oxygen to 1 L and she maintained her oxygen saturations in the low-to-mid-90s.
Because of the finding of pulmonary emboli in the splenic infarct, we elected to obtain bilateral lower-extremity ultrasound, which was negative for DVT.
On review of Mrs. Duran's medical record, she did undergo an attempt at thrombectomy of her left AV fistula on June 30, but this was unsuccessful.  She then had a right IJ tunneled dialysis catheter placed on July 1.  Left upper extremity graft ultrasound performed yesterday showed a small amount of thrombus in a segment of the graft that was not associated with significant stenosis, the left upper innominate subclavian and axillary veins were patent and negative for thrombus.
I did have the privilege of speaking with Vascular Medicine and our on-call echocardiographer.  At this time, we suspect the pulmonary emboli are a sequelae of the AV graft thrombectomy and are likely incidental and asymptomatic.  Given that there is no significant thrombus in the graft, no evidence of lower-extremity DVT, and likely Mrs. Duran is asymptomatic from the pulmonary emboli, our preference is to avoid anticoagulation if possible given her inherent increase in bleeding risk (risk factors of being on chronic hemodialysis and age).  However, we are unsure of the source of her splenic infarct.  She did undergo a prior TEE on October 31, 2001, that showed a closed foramen ovale so it would seem less likely that the splenic infarct could have resulted from any embolization of thrombus from her AV graft.  Our concern, however, is that she may have a valvular thrombus or aortic thrombus.
I subsequently met with Mrs. Duran after she had transferred to her hospital room.  She said "I feel much better than I did earlier today."  She had non-labored respirations.  I discussed our plans to perform a TEE.

[end section id="20103"]

