Vessels:  She had possible carotid bruits versus radiated murmur versus radiated thrill from her AV graft.  She had 2+ radial pulses bilaterally.  I could not easily palpate pedal pulses, but both feet were warm and appeared well-perfused.  She has a left upper arm AV fistula with a palpable thrill and some surrounding ecchymoses.General:  Mrs. Duran was sitting up comfortably in her hospital gurney in the Emergency Department room.  She was easily conversant but in short sentences because of mild conversational dyspnea.  She was elderly and chronically ill-appearing but in no acute distress.  She was a delightful woman with whom to visit.  She is hard of hearing.Musculoskeletal:  She did have changes of arthritis of her feet.Extremities:  She does have 1+ bilateral lower-extremity edema.Abdomen:  Soft, very active bowel sounds, minimal tenderness in the left upper quadrant.Psychiatric:  She was alert and oriented, maintained good eye contact, and had a very pleasant affect.  Later, she did take a nap, but she was easily arousable.Eyes:  Pupils equal.  Extraocular muscles intact.  She has a mild chronic right upper eyelid ptosis.Lungs:  Slightly diminished in the left base.  No crackles or wheezes.Heart:  Regular with a 2/6 systolic murmur versus transmitted thrill from her AV fistula.  She has a tunneled dialysis catheter in her right upper chest; there was a tiny area of irritation/erythema near the base of her neck overlying the catheter, but no clear evidence of infection.ENT:  Oropharynx was moist.Neck:  Supple.

